\label{phiequation}
\end{eqnarray}
where we use the notation $\mathcal{G}_{B {\phi}}=\mathcal{G}_{{\phi} 
B}=\frac{\partial^{2}\mathcal{G}}{\partial B \partial {\phi}}$, etc. One can rigorously  
verify that the above equations are compatible with the equations 
arising from the fact that the total action is diffeomorphism  invariant 
\cite{Ohashi:2015fma}:
\begin{eqnarray}
\nabla_{\mu} \mathcal{E}^{{\mu}{\nu}}+\frac{1}{2}\mathcal{E}_{\chi} 
\nabla^{{\nu}}\chi+\frac{1}{2}\mathcal{E}_{{\phi}} 
\nabla^{{\nu}}\phi=\frac{1}{2}\nabla_{{\mu}}T^{{\mu}{\nu}}=0.
\end{eqnarray} 

Concerning the late-time application of the above equations, one can see that the 
Friedmann equations 
(\ref{FR1}),(\ref{FR2}) can be written in the usual form, namely
\begin{eqnarray}
&&H^2=\frac{1}{3}(\rho_{DE}+\rho_m)
 \label{FR1b}
